summary: In this blog post, I break down quantum machine learning for readers with a probabilistic/Bayesian background, anchored on a real paper about mRNA secondary structure prediction by my colleagues Alexey Galda and Mihir Metkar. I cover qubits as probabilistic bits, entanglement as non-independence, and how clever problem representation (nucleotide quartets) combined with quantum sampling and classical optimization makes quantum computing practical for computational biology. Curious how a quantum computer acts as a specialized sampler for problems too large to enumerate classically?
